To position Paul Lewis for the benefit of those who haven't heard him
and who would want a sober perspective beyond the boorish macho stuff
above or my angry reply; Lewis is I think in the line, this early, of
being a natural successor to Solomon. Perhaps some will think that too
high praise for one who is still a young pianist-and of course he
still has years to develop-but that's the place in the spectrum of the
Beethoven interpretative scale he inhabits. Kovacevich for instance
has an excellent Beethoven cycle, more dramatic than Lewis, a fine
set, very satisfying. Lewis seems more nimble, has a terrific sense of
rhythm (I think here in comparison, of the last movement of Solomon's
Waldstein) and as a number of commentators have expressed in print,
seems to have a remarkable ability to bring out the emotional
important of the music in an individual but non-interventionist way.
The great Schnabel searching interpretations of say, the adagio of
opus 2 no 3, or the andante of op 109 (neither of which performance
has been quite equalled since in their beauty of pace and hanging-in-
the-air phrasing at crucial points, in my personal opinion) are
sometimes spoiled by Schnabel's not quite so exact articulation
elsewhere (eg his opening of the Hammerklavier). But Schnabel is
indispensable.

I am not saying that Lewis is as great as Schabel, I am saying that he
has a cleanness of articulation, a superb rhythmic understanding, an
apparent grasp of overall structure, and an ability especially in the
slower passages of Beethoven to convey a depth of emotion that brings
to my mind at least both Schnabel and Solomon. His performances and
recordings have been raved about. No matter, in the sense that one
arrives at one's own conclusions from one's own experience, finally.
But to dismiss him in such boorish dismissive and violent terms that
bring in the notion of his fingers needing to be broken by the
composer is very, very sad. &quot;Music hath charms to soothe the savage
breast&quot;-yet some breasts are obviously a deal more savage than others.
Andre Gide said that every age gets the Shakespeare it deserves. It
would seem that the most savage breasts get the Beethoven they
deserve, in their own minds: a violent thug.

Which is why I made my swipe about militarism.  America is of course
by no means the only country in the world with such a faction having
too much power; there is one of the biggest collection of nuclear
missiles in the world stored less than thirty miles from where I
write, in Scotland. Lots of us would enjoy our Beethoven even more if
such were to be removed.

