I think you've perfectly summed up what must be going through the
minds of a lot of listeners-- a sense of growing frustration at lost
opportunities for pianistic aggression. Lewis floats through Beethoven
as if it never threatens him and should never threaten us. Maybe he's
not threatened because he's mastered it in a way Beethoven did not (or
had not before the very end).

But actually I think Beethoven would be the first to thank Lewis for
taking his music so seriously, for managing to carve out a feeling of
timelessness and inner repose and utter certainty in the face of so
much abruptness. Maybe it is wrong to play all Beethoven like it is
late Beethoven, but the late Beethoven, at least, might very well
shake (gingerly) those precious hands and admire Lewis' ability to
arrive at such maturity so quickly when it took Beethoven so long to
get there. Lewis sees where Beethoven was going before Beethoven saw
it, that's all.

I haven't heard any of his recordings, but I listen to Lewis' live
Beethoven concerts with the certainty that deep concentration is
rewarded deeply, that the music flows without the slightest
distraction, that it bends, soars, and penetrates with neither
exaggeration nor understatement. They've worn very well on repetition,
too.

Call it wrong if you wish, but it is quite possible that you are
seriously underestimating the power of the music--even early
Beethoven--to speak through heavenly refinement rather than through
earthly spasms.

Despite all the obvious moments where a little banging would make a
point, Lewis is not slighting Beethoven's volatility; he's somehow
elevating it to a different point of view. I rather think Beethoven of
all people would appreciate the effort on his behalf.

This isn't my everyday view of Beethoven, but it's becoming clear that
Lewis is not an everyday pianist. This idea that he lacks artistic
masculinity is among the stupidest things I've ever heard. Anyone who
can maintain a long arc of such complicated music with such seeming
effortlessness has an immutable force of will and nerves of steel to
go with his heart-of-gold lyricism. To launch into an interpretation
like this that cannot tolerate the slightest raw tone or poorly timed
phrase or misjudged dynamic is to take a walk on the high-wire without
a net. This guy has guts.

--Jeff
