I am not convinced of that. Indeed, the metal frame of the modern
piano imparts a much more forceful sound than that obtained on a wood
framed piano.

Beethoven practically destroyed his instruments, if one is to believe
reports of his banging furiously to get more sound out of the damned
things. Perhaps this was due to his increasing deafness. Perhaps,
however, just to the lack of force available to this very forceful
pianist.

If Lewis can be compared to any previous pianist, it might be Wilhelm
Kempff, although in concert - I heard him do all 32 sonatas in 1970 -
his sound was far more forceful than on his DG recordings.

But Kempff had additional elements to his pianism, including a very
wide dynamic range. Just try Op. 22 (first movement, development) from
the 1950s set for proof of this. And his Hammerklavier in public was
cataclysmic in approach.

